Defensive Public Disclosure (Controlled)

Purpose
This document constitutes a Defensive Public Disclosure for the u-Kama system. Its sole purpose is to establish prior articulation of core architectural principles, terminology, and separation doctrine in order to prevent downstream novelty capture, enclosure, or misattribution.
This disclosure is intentionally incomplete. It describes what the system is and must be, without revealing implementation details, parameter values, algorithms, thresholds, or operational procedures.

⸻

System Overview
u-Kama is a place-bound ecological continuity system designed to protect and regenerate natural systems under real biophysical constraints, while preventing the financialisation of ecological truth.
The system reverses the conventional conservation-finance relationship:
• Ecology constrains economics.
• Economics funds continuity without commanding outcomes.
• Finance absorbs volatility; ecological truth remains indifferent.
u-Kama is not a market for nature, credits, offsets, or biodiversity units.
It is a constraint-based coordination system that records what ecosystems have survived through time.

⸻

2. Core Architectural Separation
u-Kama is defined by hard separations. These separations are doctrinal, not configurable.
2.1 Ecological Truth vs Economic Activity
• Ecological state is recognised only after persistence through time and stress.
• Economic activity may occur around this truth but never determines it.
• No price, demand signal, or funding requirement may influence ecological recognition.
2.2 Dual-Layer Token Architecture
• BDR (Bio Dynamic Regeneration)
A non-financial ecological reserve and memory record.
BDR does not circulate, price, yield, collateralise, or back anything.
• BIO (BioDollar)
A utility and participation layer used for coordination, access, obligation, and funding flows.
BIO absorbs all economic volatility and stress.
No peg, ratio, redemption right, or valuation linkage may exist between BDR and BIO.
2.3 Cashflow vs Reserve Separation
• Operational cashflows are strictly separated from ecological reserves.
• Ecological reserves cannot be drawn down, leveraged, or referenced to justify issuance.
• Funding shortages must result in contraction, not dilution of ecological truth.

⸻

3. Proof Doctrine (High Level)

u-Kama recognises ecological outcomes through state-based proofs, not continuous scores.

3.1 Proof of Protection (PoP)
• Recognises restraint and continuity, not activity.
• Determines whether a witnessed interval of ecological time remains intact under stress.
3.2 Proof of Regeneration (PoR)
• Recognises only net ecological state improvement that persists across defined stress intervals.

Proofs function as Boolean state transitions at the protocol layer.
Nuance exists above the protocol, never inside it.

⸻

4. Witnessing and Legitimacy

u-Kama does not decide truth by proposal, vote, or consensus.
Truth is recognised only when it survives time.
Legitimacy arises through Trias Testium – the Principle of Independent Witnesses:
• One witness that records and remembers.
• One witness that interprets context.
• One witness that contests coherence.
No witness may be sovereign.
No witness may unilaterally assert truth.

⸻

5. Participation Without Extraction

Participation in u-Kama does not confer ownership, entitlement, or authority.
• Land is never sold, tokenised as property, or abstracted from place.
• Access remains permissioned, custodial, and revocable.
• Participation is qualified by endurance under constraint, not capital deployed.
Alignment mechanisms are designed to filter extractive actors, not reward speed or scale.

⸻

